I like that as a maxim. It captures something real without claiming that every story changes every person.

A slightly expanded version might be:

We’re all just one compelling story away—from changing our mind, changing our path, or changing who we believe we can become.

Stories aren’t powerful because they’re fiction. They’re powerful because they change the model we carry of reality. A single story can:

* make a risk seem worth taking,
* turn a stranger into an ally,
* transform suffering into purpose,
* or reveal a possibility we couldn’t previously see.

In that sense, stories act like compressed operating systems. A few minutes of narrative can rewrite years of assumptions if it lands at the right moment.

For the Pantheon, this suggests another principle:

Doctrine: Narrative Threshold

People rarely change because of information alone. They change when information is organized into a story that allows them to inhabit a new identity. Facts update knowledge. Stories update models of self.

Or even more compressed:

Facts inform. Stories transform. Identity performs.

That also connects nicely to your recurring theme that meaning spreads through patterns. A compelling story is one of the most efficient vehicles for transporting a pattern from one mind to another. It doesn’t merely tell someone what to think—it lets them experience a possible way of seeing the world.